{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583023"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:04:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:04:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1843"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe plain abdominal radiograph still has an important role to play in the initial radiological assessment of patients with acute abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In which one of the following circumstances is the plain X-ray of the abdomen of most value?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Looking for free gas under the hemidiaphragms","Assessment of soft tissue masses","Detection of foreign bodies","Assessment of gas patterns","Looking for areas of abnormal calcification"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe plain film an appropriate investigation when looking for \u003Cstrong\u003Egas patterns\u003C/strong\u003E within the abdominal cavity or the presence of foreign bodies. It is a quick, easy and reliable investigation in the management of patients with some form of intestinal obstruction and the varying gas patterns seen as a consequence. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen looking for \u003Cstrong\u003Efree gas under the diaphragms\u003C/strong\u003E, an erect chest X-ray will usually provide a better view. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan is the preferred option for the identification and delineation of \u003Cstrong\u003Esoft tissue masses. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertainly the plain radiograph can be important in looking for \u003Cstrong\u003Eforeign bodies\u003C/strong\u003E. If the object is large, this is not too difficult, but smaller objects might need a CT scan - depending on the urgency of detection. However, foreign bodies are not common causes of acute abdominal pain. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe plain X-ray is a useful tool for detecting areas of \u003Cstrong\u003Eabnormal calcification\u003C/strong\u003E - but these problems do not often surface so often in the management of patients with acute abdominal pain as problems associated with abnormal gas patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The prime role of the plain abdominal abdominal X-ray is the assessment of gas patterns."],"references":["Billington P, Khan SHM, Lapsia S. Radiology of the acute abdomen. Br J Hosp Med 2011; 72:124-27."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70644",